The '''art of Urartu''' refers to a historical and regional type of art from [[Urartu]], the ancient state of [[Western Asia]] which existed in the period 13-6 century BC in the [[Armenian Highland]]. The art of Urartu was strongly influenced by the nearby [[Assyria]], the most prominent state of that period in the region. It peaked around the 8th century BC but was mostly looted and destroyed with the fall of Urartu about a century later.<ref name=c148>Chahin, 148</ref><ref name=brit>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/619349/Urartu Urartu], Encyclopedia Britannica online</ref>
[[File:Urartian Art 04a~.jpg|thumb|right|Detail of a [[bronze]] throne of [[List of kings of Urartu|Urartian kings]]]]

== Overview ==
Urartian art was heavily influenced by the neighboring Assyria, and despite the obvious stylistic differences, has long been considered a branch of the Assyrian art. Urartian art is characterized by 1) a more rigorous than in other cultures of the Ancient East following the [[Aesthetic canon|canon]], 2) preference to [[Ornament (architecture)|ornaments]] rather than life scenes, and 3) copying old samples instead of improving them.<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"><U+041F><U+0438><U+043E><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0411>. <U+0411>. <U+0418><U+0441><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+0423><U+0440><U+0430><U+0440><U+0442><U+0443> VIII<U+2014>VI <U+0432><U+0432>. <U+0434><U+043E> <U+043D>. <U+044D>. (The Art of Urartu, 8-6 century BC). Publishing House of [[Hermitage]], Leningrad, 1962</ref><ref name="Afanaseva1968">{{cite book|author=<U+0410><U+0444><U+0430><U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+044C><U+0435><U+0432><U+0430> <U+0412>. <U+041A>., <U+0414><U+044C><U+044F><U+043A><U+043E><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432> <U+0418>. <U+041C>. |title=<U+0418><U+0441><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+041F><U+0435><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+043D><U+0435><U+0439> <U+0410><U+0437><U+0438><U+0438> 2 <U+2014> <U+0441><U+0435><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+0438><U+043D><U+044B> 1 <U+0442><U+044B><U+0441><U+044F><U+0447><U+0435><U+043B><U+0435><U+0442><U+0438><U+044F> <U+0434><U+043E> <U+043D>. <U+044D>.. <U+041F><U+0430><U+043C><U+044F><U+0442><U+043D><U+0438><U+043A><U+0438> <U+043C><U+0438><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+0438><U+0441><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0430> (The Art of Western Asia from 2nd to the middle of 1st millennium BC. Monuments of world art). Issue 2 (1st series). The Art of the Ancient Orient|publisher=<U+0418><U+0441><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E>|place=Moscow|year=1968}}</ref> As a result, the style of Urartian craftsmen remained unchanged for several centuries and was gradually simplified.<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"/> Urartian art was relatively poorly characterized until 1950s, when major archeological work was started at the ancient Urartian cities [[Teishebaini]] and [[Erebuni]] and many Urartian [[cuneiform]] tables Urartu were deciphered.

==Bronze statuettes ==
Although Urartian masters were capable of producing large bronze statue, not even their fragments have been found so far. Literature mentions that while looting the city of [[Musasir]], Assyrians removed a bronze statue of [[List of kings of Urartu|King]] [[Argishti I]] weighing 60 [[Talent (measurement)|talents]] (about 1,8 tons). Small bronze art items of Urartu were exclusively made for the king's palace and are divided into three groups: [[throne]] decorations, ornament on copper boilers and rare statuettes of Urartian gods. 

===Throne decorations ===
Between 1877 and 1885, local treasure hunters sold a few small bronze fragments to several European museums. These fragments later turned out to be parts of one and the same Urartian king's throne. They were cast in bronze into a mold and then gilded by wrapping in thin [[gold]] sheets. The fragments are currently preserved in the [[British Museum]], [[Hermitage]], [[Louvre]], [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] and in private collections in [[Paris]] and [[Brussels]].

