===Boiler decorations ===
{{double image|right|UrartianCaldron02.jpg|165|UrartianCaldron03~.jpg|290|Left: boiler with bull heads found in [[Van Province]], Turkey. Right: boiler from a [[Phrygia]]n city with figures assigned to the god [[Shivini]].<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"/><ref name=ank>[[Museum of Anatolian Civilizations]], [[Ankara]], Turkey</ref>}}

Boiler decorations are the best preserved objects of Urartian bronze art; therefore, they were used in the early 20th century to identify the Urartian style in art.<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"/> The decorated [[copper]] boilers were apparently used for ritual ceremonies. For example, the annals of the Assyrian king [[Sargon II]] mention a bronze vessel filled with the wine being part of the sacrifice to God [[<U+1E2A>aldi]]. 

The bronze statuettes were cast separately and then attached to the boiler. They include bull heads and winged deities, possibly god [[Shivini]] and his wife [[Tushpuea]].<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"/> The technique of [[casting]] bronze ornaments spread from [[Urartu]] to the neighboring countries, in particular to [[Phrygia]], and then to Europe. Urartian boiler ornaments were found in [[Rhodes (city)|Rhodes]], [[Athens]], [[Boeotia]], [[Delphi]], [[Olympia]] and [[Etruscan]] tombs. Initially, many Urartian decorations have been taken by researchers in [[Antiquity|ancient]], but since the 1950s, after detailed studies of these ornaments boilers have been identified and unanimously ranked as the monuments of Urartu art <ref name="Pallottino">{{cite journal|author=Pallottino, M. |title=Urartu, Greece and Etruria|journal= East and West|volume=9|issue=1<U+2013>2|place=Rome|year=1958}}</ref><ref name="Amandry">Amandry P. Objets orientaux en Gr<U+00E8>ce et en Italie aux VIIIe et VIIe si<U+00E8>cles avant J<U+00E9>sus-Christ, Syria, XXXV, 1 <U+2013> 2, Paris 1958</ref><ref name="Maxwell-Hyslop">Maxwell, M., Hyslop KR ''Urartian Bronzes in Etruscan Tombs'', Iraq, XVIII, 2, 1956</ref>. Scientists have even been instances when the Urartian bronze figures for the boilers used by other nations again to decorate the new vessels.

===Statuettes of gods ===
{{double image|left|Tesheiba02~.jpg|150|Arubani02~.jpg|200|Left: god of weather [[Theispas|Teisheba]], found in 1941 during the excavations at [[Karmir Blur]], in the ruins of the Urartian fortress of [[Teishebaini]] named in honor of the god. Right: goddess [[Arubani]], wife of the god <U+1E2A>aldi.}}

Only three bronze statuettes depicting Urartian deities have been preserved. One, possibly of the god [[<U+1E2A>aldi]], is stored in the British Museum, and two others are in the National Museum of History of Armenia (copy in the Erebuni Museum, Yerevan, see image).

== Weapons ==
=== Helmets===
{{double image|right|Helmet08.jpg|130|Urartu_Helmet_Fragment_2~.jpg|250|Helmet of the Urartu king [[Sarduri II]] found at [[Karmir Blur]] near [[Teishebaini]].<ref name=mus2>National Museum of History of Armenia, Yerevan</ref> The inscription on the helmet reads: "Sarduri, son of [[Argishti I|Argishti]] dedicates this helmet to God <U+1E2A>aldi".<ref name="PerevodP2"><U+041F><U+0438><U+043E><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0439>, <U+0411>. <U+0411>. <U+041A><U+0430><U+0440><U+043C><U+0438><U+0440>-<U+0411><U+043B><U+0443><U+0440> II, <U+0420><U+0435><U+0437><U+0443><U+043B><U+044C><U+0442><U+0430><U+0442><U+044B> <U+0440><U+0430><U+0441><U+043A><U+043E><U+043F><U+043E><U+043A> 1949<U+2014>1950 (Karmir Blur II, Results of Excavations 1949<U+2013>1950), Academy of Sciences of Armenia, Yerevan, 1952 </ref> Right: detail of the helmet depicting the [[Tree of life (biblical)|tree of life]]}}

Numerous Urartian helmets have been recovered, more than 20 only during the excavations of [[Teishebaini]]. Royal ceremonial helmets did not differ in shape from simple combat helmets but contained engraved images.

=== Shields=== 
A few decorative bronze Urartian shields have been found near Van (they are stored in the British Museum and Berlin museums) and 14 were excavated at [[Karmir Blur]]. They have diameters ranging between 70 and 100 cm and were not made for combat, as judged from the thickness of metal and the character of the handles. All these shields contain concentric circles of lions and bulls which were designed so that no figure would appear upside down. The images were first stamped and then deepened with various instruments. Assyrian king Sargon II described six golden Urartian shields, which were looted in [[Musasir]], weighing 6.5 kg each. They have not been recovered thus far. 

