=== Armor=== 
{{double image|left|Urartian_Belt01.jpg|380|Urartian_Belt06.jpg|256|Protective belts of Urartian archers. Left: remains of an iron belt found at [[Arin Berd]], [[Erebuni]].<ref name=mus/> Right: bronze belt found near Van.<ref name=ank/>}}
{{clear}}
Poorly preserved remains of Urartian [[Mail (armour)|mail]] of [[Argishti I]] were excavated at [[Teishebaini]].<ref name=mus/> Entire (or parts of) wide bronze belts were found in Turkey (Altyn-Tepe), [[Iran]] ([[Lake Urmia]]) and Armenia (Karmir Blur). The belts were about 1 meter long and 12 cm wide and aimed to protected archers.

=== Jewelry===
Jewelry of Urartu had two gradations: ornaments made of precious metals and stones for the king and his family and their simplified bronze versions used by the riches. Many jewelry items were also used as amulets.<ref name="Esayan">{{cite journal|author=<U+0415><U+0441><U+0430><U+044F><U+043D> <U+0421>.|title=<U+042E><U+0432><U+0435><U+043B><U+0438><U+0440><U+043D><U+043E><U+0435> <U+0438><U+0441><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+0423><U+0440><U+0430><U+0440><U+0442><U+0443> (Jewelry art of Urartu) |journal=<U+0418><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E>-<U+0444><U+0438><U+043B><U+043E><U+043B><U+043E><U+0433><U+0438><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0436><U+0443><U+0440><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B>|place=Yerevan|volume=3|year=2003}}</ref> Annals of the Assyrian king [[Sargon II]] mention vast amounts of Urartian jewelry items made of silver and gold which were taken from Musasir in 714 BC.<ref name=c148/> They are not preserved and  some may have been melted by treasure hunters.<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"/> The two largest recovered jewelry items are shown below. They are the pectoral decoration excavated at the late Urartian capital [[Rusahinili]] and the cover of the boiler found at Teishebaini. Smaller items include golden pins, earrings, a [[bracelet]] and a few medallions. Jewelry was worn in Urartu by both man and women. Women's jewelry usually portrayed Urartian goddess [[Arubani]], wife of <U+1E2A>aldi <U+2013> the supreme god of Urartu. Also common are Mesopotamian motifs such as [[tree of life]] and [[winged sun]]. More accessible jewelry included bronze bracelets and earrings and [[carnelian]] beads.<ref name="Esayan"/>

