|}

{{double image|right|AchaemenidGoblet02.jpg|170|AchaemenidGoblet01.jpg|207|Silver [[rhyton]]s of [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]] era found in 1968 at the foot of the hill Arin Bird.<ref name=mus>Erebuni Museum, Erevan, Armenia</ref> Their combining elements of eastern, Greek and Urartu art confirms the influence of Urartu art on the nearby countries.<ref name="Arakelyan"><U+0410><U+0440><U+0430><U+043A><U+0435><U+043B><U+044F><U+043D> <U+0411>.<U+041D>. <U+041A><U+043B><U+0430><U+0434> <U+0441><U+0435><U+0440><U+0435><U+0431><U+0440><U+044F><U+043D><U+044B><U+0445> <U+0438><U+0437><U+0434><U+0435><U+043B><U+0438><U+0439> <U+0438><U+0437> <U+042D><U+0440><U+0435><U+0431><U+0443><U+043D><U+0438> (Silver treasures excavated at Erebuni) Soviet Archaeology, 1971, Vol. 1</ref>}}

Many features of Urartian art were preserved in the neighboring countries after the fall of Urartu in the 6th century BC. Observations by [[Boris Piotrovsky]] suggest that decoration and production techniques of [[Scythians|scythian]] belts and [[scabbard]]s were borrowed from Urartu.<ref name="Piotrovskiy1962"/> The Urartian way of decorating boilers spread over the ancient world, and it is believed that [[Art of Armenia|Armenian]] and South [[Georgia]]n art were partly based on the Urartian traditions.<ref name="Piotrovskiy1959"/><ref Name="Stepanyan"><U+0421><U+0442><U+0435><U+043F><U+0430><U+043D><U+044F><U+043D> <U+041D>. [http://www.fluteric.info/Armenia/Fine_Arts/title.htm <U+0418><U+0441><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+0410><U+0440><U+043C><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0438>: <U+0447><U+0435><U+0440><U+0442><U+044B> <U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E>-<U+0445><U+0443><U+0434><U+043E><U+0436><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+043E><U+0433><U+043E> <U+0440><U+0430><U+0437><U+0432><U+0438><U+0442><U+0438><U+044F>] (The Art of Armenia: the features of historical and artistic development). Soviet Artist, Moscow, 1989, ISBN 5-269-00042-3</ref>

